Aim
To study Arduino boards and their applications in embedded systems and IoT.
Introduction
Arduino is an open-source microcontroller platform used for embedded systems, automation, robotics, and
Internet of Things (IoT) applications. Arduino boards are easy to program and interface with sensors, motors, LEDs,
displays, and communication modules.
Arduino uses Embedded C/C++ programming through the Arduino IDE. Due to its simple hardware and software
environment, Arduino is widely used by students, beginners, engineers, and researchers for developing electronic
projects and automation systems.
Arduino boards can receive input from sensors, process the data, and control output devices based on the
program logic.
Features of Arduino
• Open-source platform
• Easy programming using Arduino IDE
• Supports Embedded C/C++
• Supports sensor interfacing
• USB programming support
• Digital and analog I/O pins
• Low power consumption
• Suitable for IoT and automation projects
Types of Arduino Boards
Arduino Uno
Arduino Uno is the most commonly used Arduino board for beginners and embedded projects.
Specifications
• Microcontroller: ATmega328P
• Operating Voltage: 5V
• Digital I/O Pins: 14
• Analog Input Pins: 6
• Clock Speed: 16 MHz
Arduino Nano
Arduino Nano is a compact version of Arduino Uno mainly used in small embedded applications.
Specifications
• Microcontroller: ATmega328P
• Operating Voltage: 5V
• Compact size
• Breadboard friendly
• USB support available
Arduino Mega
Arduino Mega is used for large projects requiring more pins and memory.
Specifications
• Microcontroller: ATmega2560
• Digital I/O Pins: 54
• Analog Input Pins: 16
• Large memory capacity
• Clock Speed: 16 MHz
Arduino Leonardo
Arduino Leonardo contains built-in USB communication support.
Specifications
• Microcontroller: ATmega32U4
• Built-in USB communication
• 20 digital I/O pins
• 12 analog input pins
Arduino LilyPad
Arduino LilyPad is specially designed for wearable electronics and smart clothing applications.
Specifications
• Lightweight and flexible design
• Sewable pads for stitching
• Low power consumption
• Supports wearable sensors
Components of Arduino Uno
Microcontroller
The ATmega328P microcontroller performs all processing operations.
Digital Pins
Used for digital input and output operations.
Analog Pins
Used to read analog sensor values.
USB Port
Used for programming and power supply.
Power Jack
Provides external power supply to the board.
Reset Button
Used to restart the Arduino board.
Working Principle
Arduino boards read data from sensors and process the information using the microcontroller. Based on the
programmed instructions, Arduino controls output devices such as LEDs, motors, relays, buzzers, and displays.
For IoT applications, Arduino can communicate with cloud platforms using WiFi or Bluetooth modules.
